{"event_type":"group_checkpoint_event","schema_version":"2.0.1","date":"2026-04-06 17:40:52","data":{"uuid":"6bc539f2-db49-4ed0-a8a9-659d11428cf5","name":"Fatty Acid Oxidation Disorders","description":"Fatty acid metabolism consists of catabolic processes that generate energy, and anabolic processes that create biologically important molecules (triglycerides, phospholipids, second messengers, local hormones and ketone bodies). Fatty acids are a family of molecules classified within the lipid macronutrient class. Fatty acid β-oxidation is a multi-step process by which fatty acids are broken down by various tissues to produce energy. It involves first getting the fatty acid into the cytosol and then transferring it to the mitochondria where β-oxidation takes place. β-oxidation involves: activation to acyl-CoA by conjugation with coenzyme A in the cytosol, conversion to acylcarnitine for transport across the mitochondrial membrane and conversion back to acyl-CoA inside the mitochondrion where fatty acid oxidation (β-oxidation) takes place.

Fatty acid oxidation disorders (FAODs) are autosomal recessive conditions caused by defects in the pathway, which comprises at least 20 individual steps. The Fatty Acid Oxidation (FAO) GCEP was created to examine the strength of association between FAOD and genes implicated in these disorders using the ClinGen Clinical Validity Framework (Strande &amp; Riggs et al, 2017). For this purpose, a comprehensive list of 30 FAO genes for curation was developed, including 8 genes that were found to be on more than one gene panel offering FAO testing.

**The Fatty Acid Oxidation Disorders GCEP was formed in 2018, and their initial scope of work included 30 genes thought to be associated with fatty acid β-oxidation. The group completed evaluation of these genes in 2021, and their findings are described in PMID: 31399326. The General IEM GCEP now re-evaluates these curations on a ClinGen protocol specified periodicity, as described in the [ClinGen recuration procedure.](https://clinicalgenome.org/site/assets/files/2164/clingen_standard_gene-disease_validity_recuration_procedures_v1.pdf)**","caption":null,"icon_url":null,"status":"inactive","status_date":"2022-02-14T23:47:01+00:00","type":"gcep","coi":"https://gpm.clinicalgenome.org/coi-group/6bc539f2-db49-4ed0-a8a9-659d11428cf5","members":[{"uuid":"89bcda21-1e77-4d4d-9be1-56a47c93243c","first_name":"Meredith","last_name":"Weaver","roles":["Grant Liaison"],"additional_permissions":[],"institution":"American College of Medical Genetics & Genomics","credentials":["PhD","CGC"],"code_of_conduct":{"status":"current","current_version":"1.0.0","completed_at":"2026-03-16T12:37:24+00:00","expires_at":"2027-03-16T12:37:24+00:00","days_remaining":343},"profile_photo":"https://gpm.clinicalgenome.org/profile-photos/CxaI5tlZwuGY40GUJvwyMRcNLZEoDE3JHGOVrxK8.png"},{"uuid":"67c2f22c-f4d0-4c48-b96f-372795f3a3ee","first_name":"Raquel","last_name":"Fernandez","roles":["Coordinator"],"additional_permissions":[],"institution":"American College of Medical Genetics & Genomics","credentials":["BSc"],"code_of_conduct":{"status":"current","current_version":"1.0.0","completed_at":"2026-03-12T15:12:19+00:00","expires_at":"2027-03-12T15:12:19+00:00","days_remaining":339},"profile_photo":"https://gpm.clinicalgenome.org/profile-photos/6umcflmvuasOXxSJdZMwCEAmU4VwvxBrNxwYluMv.jpg","email":"RFernandez@acmg.net"},{"uuid":"31f1e085-bfc1-4ed5-83ad-37f1a7bfa54e","first_name":"Heather","last_name":"Baudet","roles":["Chair"],"additional_permissions":[],"institution":"University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill","credentials":["MD","PhD"],"code_of_conduct":{"status":"current","current_version":"1.0.0","completed_at":"2026-04-06T15:05:57+00:00","expires_at":"2027-04-06T15:05:57+00:00","days_remaining":364},"profile_photo":"https://gpm.clinicalgenome.org/profile-photos/HCBrkiCig2cqMR2gMcw1zVWtUiCiUW1hOJeImdkb.png","email":"hbaudet@mac.com"},{"uuid":"a8546d38-e0e5-4dc9-80e4-9736a4ed6fbc","first_name":"Rong","last_name":"Mao","roles":["Chair"],"additional_permissions":[],"institution":"ARUP Laboratories/University of Utah","credentials":["MD"],"code_of_conduct":{"status":"current","current_version":"1.0.0","completed_at":"2026-03-23T19:04:09+00:00","expires_at":"2027-03-23T19:04:09+00:00","days_remaining":351},"profile_photo":"https://gpm.clinicalgenome.org/profile-photos/HZ9DhP89VTBBCCWMlzTjv7aa7UXq8sFXva4B8i93.png","email":"rong.mao@aruplab.com"},{"uuid":"9dff3b72-755c-4c2e-8e9d-18fb975c565b","first_name":"Jennifer","last_name":"McGlaughon","roles":["Biocurator"],"additional_permissions":[],"institution":"LabCorp","credentials":["PhD"],"code_of_conduct":{"status":"current","current_version":"1.0.0","completed_at":"2026-03-13T14:53:28+00:00","expires_at":"2027-03-13T14:53:28+00:00","days_remaining":340}},{"uuid":"f75543a5-fb8e-4140-bd53-86d282972436","first_name":"Annette","last_name":"Feigenbaum","roles":["Expert"],"additional_permissions":[],"institution":"University of California, San Diego","credentials":["MBBCh","FRCPc","dabmgg"],"code_of_conduct":{"status":"current","current_version":"1.0.0","completed_at":"2026-03-30T02:33:19+00:00","expires_at":"2027-03-30T02:33:19+00:00","days_remaining":357}},{"uuid":"908829e3-dceb-4944-98aa-4d503dc1c409","first_name":"Marzia","last_name":"Pasquali","roles":["Expert"],"additional_permissions":[],"institution":"University of Utah","credentials":["PhD"],"code_of_conduct":{"status":"current","current_version":"1.0.0","completed_at":"2026-03-24T16:07:09+00:00","expires_at":"2027-03-24T16:07:09+00:00","days_remaining":351},"profile_photo":"https://gpm.clinicalgenome.org/profile-photos/uTNkYj3uaC4Toe51ITDKZ8eAnLm0Xldfjhkf9HLs.jpg"}],"expert_panel":{"uuid":"6bc539f2-db49-4ed0-a8a9-659d11428cf5","affiliation_id":"40010","name":"Fatty Acid Oxidation Disorders","short_name":"FAO","scope_description":null,"membership_description":null,"type":"gcep","date_completed":"2018-07-18T04:00:00.000000Z","inactive_date":"2025-07-25","current_step":1,"all_genes":[],"gcep_final_approval":"2018-07-18T04:00:00.000000Z"},"parent":{"uuid":"2e312275-a400-47ab-a34c-cad7698703cf","name":"Inborn Errors Metabolism","type":"cdwg","status":"active"}}}

{"event_type":"group_checkpoint_event","schema_version":"2.0.1","date":"2026-04-06 17:40:46","data":{"uuid":"21c56140-cfe6-45f9-ab2a-aa3412c0daeb","name":"Antibody Deficiencies","description":"<div>The focus of the Antibody Deficiencies Gene Curation Expert Panel will be to curate genes associated with various inborn errors of immunity that result in antibody deficiencies (decrease in one or more immunoglobulin isotypes) with or without quantitative B cell defects and other phenotypic manifestations. The gene list contains 41 genes primarily derived from the 2019 IUIS classification ([Tangye et al, J Clin Immunol, 2020, 40: 24-64](https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s10875-019-00737-x)). The gene list has been organized in order of priority for curation. Inborn errors of immunity represent monogenic defects affecting various components of the immune system resulting in a multitude of clinical phenotypes with variable expressivity and penetrance, as well as inheritance patterns.

**The Antibody Deficiencies GCEP (AD-GCEP was formed in 2020, and their initial scope of work included 65 genes thought to be associated with humoral (predominantly antibody) immunodeficiencies\]. The group completed evaluation of these genes in 2023, and their findings are described in \[“Curation of gene-disease relationships in primary antibody deficiencies using the ClinGen validation framework’, by Nieto-Patlan A et al, J Allergy Clin Immunol, 2025 (PMID: 39826876; DOI: 10.1016/j.jaci.2025.01.005)\]. The \[Primary Immune Regulatory Disorders GCEP\] now re-evaluates these curations on a periodic basis, as described in the ClinGen recuration procedure.** *Inactive Date 8/7/25*

</div>","caption":null,"icon_url":null,"status":"inactive","status_date":"2022-02-14T23:47:01+00:00","type":"gcep","coi":"https://gpm.clinicalgenome.org/coi-group/21c56140-cfe6-45f9-ab2a-aa3412c0daeb","members":[{"uuid":"7fa8442e-eb91-4088-bbd5-4b45d2c242f0","first_name":"Haley","last_name":"Garrett","roles":["Coordinator"],"additional_permissions":[],"institution":"UNC Biocuration and Coordination Core","credentials":["MPH"],"code_of_conduct":{"status":"current","current_version":"1.0.0","completed_at":"2026-03-09T20:24:27+00:00","expires_at":"2027-03-09T20:24:27+00:00","days_remaining":337},"profile_photo":"https://gpm.clinicalgenome.org/profile-photos/NhodsuTi9nLEE4k4g4b9YjUrWrQferVPlC4TdBPh.jpg","email":"Haley_Garrett@med.unc.edu"}],"expert_panel":{"uuid":"21c56140-cfe6-45f9-ab2a-aa3412c0daeb","affiliation_id":"40080","name":"Antibody Deficiencies","short_name":"Ab Def","scope_description":null,"membership_description":null,"type":"gcep","date_completed":"2020-10-21T04:00:00.000000Z","inactive_date":"2026-02-10","current_step":1,"all_genes":[],"gcep_final_approval":"2020-10-21T04:00:00.000000Z"},"parent":{"uuid":"a6a8a8d6-9c86-4874-a34c-ca9ecdf66d25","name":"Immunology","type":"cdwg","status":"active"}}}

{"event_type":"group_checkpoint_event","schema_version":"2.0.1","date":"2026-04-06 17:40:39","data":{"uuid":"5c6d36bc-09fc-4b54-9c11-44ceb14c34b0","name":"Histone H3 SC","description":"The H3 expert panel will develop a sustainable workflow for systematic consensus review of oncogenic alterations in *H3-3A (H3F3A), H3C1 (HIST1H3A), H3C2 (HIST1H3B),* and other histone H3 encoding genes that drive tumor and response to targeted therapy. As the nomenclature of histone H3 varies greatly within the literature ([Table 1 &amp; 2](https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1gCJw-QN1MegCnjQVHYt3ikb-RmXgRN1aG0Ls42Mf5M0/edit?usp=sharing)), we will focus on harmonization at the gene variant level. Somatic single nucleotide variants (SNVs) in H3 encoding genes related to their diagnostic, prognostic and therapeutic significance will be curated. The group will concentrate on further specifying the AMP/ASCO/CAP guidelines (PMID: [27993330](https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/27993330)) and piloting the ClinGen/CGC/VICC Oncogenicity SOP for somatic variant classification on H3 alterations. After consensus classification, the panel will make these interpretations publicly available through CIViC and ClinVar knowledgebases.

The workflow will also integrate clinicopathological information (age of onset, location, pattern of infiltration) in the curation of H3 variants, as it is crucial for the accurate diagnosis and prognostication of histone-mutant gliomas. Two histone-mutant gliomas subtypes have been defined in the latest WHO Classification of Tumours of the Central Nervous System (5th edition, 2021) based on their location and amino acid alteration (‘diffuse midline glioma, H3 K27-altered’ and ‘diffuse hemispheric glioma, H3 G34-mutant’). Both entities unfortunately have a dismal prognosis and are designated as CNS WHO Grade 4. Recently however, other glioma subtypes with non-infiltrative or low grade histomorphologies have also been found to harbor H3 K27 mutations, without exhibiting the same aggressive clinical course. Current clinical practice recommendations suggest avoiding classifying such tumors as “diffuse midline glioma, H3 K27-altered”; however, further investigation is required to determine if such entities warrant separate classification. Thus, the H3 expert panel workflow will reflect the need to integrate clinical information for precise curation and classification of all gliomas harboring H3 variants.

While the above efforts will be initially conducted for glial tumors, this SC-VCEP will subsequently expand the scope of its guideline specifications to the annotation of additional Histone H3 SNVs (e.g., H3 K36M and H3 G34W) involved in other mesenchymal and epithelial tumor types. The aim would be to apply the newly created and approved rules to generate expert-panel approved variant submissions.","caption":null,"icon_url":null,"status":"applying","status_date":"2022-02-14T23:47:01+00:00","type":"vcep","coi":"https://gpm.clinicalgenome.org/coi-group/5c6d36bc-09fc-4b54-9c11-44ceb14c34b0","members":[{"uuid":"4ddb233c-659a-4169-bfe6-69a50d80195e","first_name":"Jason","last_name":"Saliba","roles":["Coordinator"],"additional_permissions":[],"institution":"Washington University in St. Louis","credentials":["PhD"],"code_of_conduct":{"status":"current","current_version":"1.0.0","completed_at":"2026-03-10T19:35:53+00:00","expires_at":"2027-03-10T19:35:53+00:00","days_remaining":338},"profile_photo":"https://gpm.clinicalgenome.org/profile-photos/Ykca8YXravbLq92srIUSTygAjM6KldmvMSQiEt3Y.jpg","email":"jsaliba@wustl.edu"},{"uuid":"5d383b8c-9148-45a6-9c8a-5bf8425a8e20","first_name":"Arpad","last_name":"Danos","roles":["Biocurator","Biocurator trainer"],"additional_permissions":[],"institution":"Washington University in St. Louis","credentials":["PhD"],"code_of_conduct":{"status":"missing","current_version":"1.0.0","completed_at":null,"expires_at":null,"days_remaining":null}},{"uuid":"09346bce-d36d-4f31-9505-5550c63982eb","first_name":"Cameron","last_name":"Grisdale","roles":["Biocurator"],"additional_permissions":[],"institution":"BC Cancer Agency","credentials":["PhD"],"code_of_conduct":{"status":"missing","current_version":"1.0.0","completed_at":null,"expires_at":null,"days_remaining":null}},{"uuid":"fd946be8-b477-477b-8d55-2e5029b25c25","first_name":"David","last_name":"Meredith","roles":["Chair"],"additional_permissions":["info-edit","application-read","application-edit","a